"""
mkt-original — 2 Samuel 12–13
run: python3 scripts/zc-original-2samuel-12-13.py

Ch12: Nathan's parable and its aftermath — sin, confession, forgiveness, consequences
Ch13: Amnon and Tamar — David's failure of household justice; Absalom's revenge
Key terms: māšāl, bāzâ/nāʾaṣ, heʿĕḇîr (forensic forgiveness), nəḇālâ, šōmēmâ
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

SAMUEL2 = {
  "12": {
    "1": "<p><strong>wayyišlaḥ YHWH et-nāṯān el-dawid</strong>: 'YHWH sent Nathan to David.' The prophetic messenger formula establishes Nathan's authority as YHWH's emissary. The form he uses is a <em>māšāl</em> — a comparison story or parable — which draws the listener in as a judge before revealing him as the defendant. This rhetorical strategy of concealed application is distinctive in OT prophetic literature and is replicated by Jesus in several confrontational parables (Matt 21:33-46).</p>",
    "2": "<p>'The rich man had very many flocks and herds.' The parable's economic realism — detailed distribution of assets — grounds the moral point in material terms. The disproportion between the rich man's holdings and the poor man's single lamb is established before the occasion for sin arises. <em>ṣōʾn ûḇāqār harbēh məʾōd</em> (very many small and large livestock) — the abundance that makes the theft more egregious, not less.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'But the poor man had only one little ewe lamb (<em>kiḇśâ ʾaḥat qəṭannâ</em>).' The adjectives accumulate — <em>ʾaḥat</em> (one, only), <em>qəṭannâ</em> (small) — and the lamb is described in terms of household intimacy: bought (<em>wayyiqqānehā</em>), raised by him (<em>wayḥayyehā</em>), grew up with his children, ate his food, drank from his cup, lay in his arms. The term <em>kəḇitô</em> (like his daughter) personalizes the attachment. The poor man's attachment to the lamb is the OT's way of expressing what genuine love for another looks like — not possessive desire but invested, relational care.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'A traveler (<em>ʾôrēaḥ</em>) came to the rich man.' The arrival of a guest creates the moral occasion. Hospitality was an absolute social obligation in the ancient Near East; failing to honor a guest was a serious breach. The rich man <em>wayyaḥmōl</em> (spared) his own flock — the same verb used for Saul's sparing of Agag and the best livestock in 1 Sam 15:9, where David's predecessor was condemned for the same word. The rich man appropriates the poor man's lamb for the guest rather than using his own vast resources.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'David burned with anger (<em>wayyiḥar ʾap dāwid</em>) against the man and said to Nathan: As YHWH lives, the man who has done this deserves to die (<em>ben-māweṯ haʾîš haʿōśeh zōʾt</em>).' David invokes the oath formula <em>ḥay YHWH</em> (as YHWH lives) in pronouncing a capital verdict on the parable's subject — a verdict he does not know he is pronouncing on himself. <em>Ben-māweṯ</em> (son of death/deserving death) is the legal formula for a capital offense in Israel.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'He shall restore the lamb fourfold (<em>wəʾeṯ-hakkiḇśâ yəšallēm ʾarbaʿtāyim</em>), because he did this thing, and because he had no pity.' The fourfold restitution cites Exod 22:1 — the specific penalty for stealing a sheep. David's legal precision is ironic: he applies the Torah's restitution law with confidence, not knowing that Nathan's parable maps directly onto his own actions. The clause <em>ʾăšer lo-ḥāmal</em> (because he had no pity) echoes the verb from v4 — the rich man showed no mercy; David's verdict identifies this pitilessness as the heart of the offense.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>attah ha-ish</strong>: 'You are the man!' The three-word accusation is the most dramatic prophetic confrontation in the OT. The switch from third person (the man in the parable) to second person (you) collapses the hermeneutical distance David had maintained. Nathan then cites YHWH's gifts: anointing as king, deliverance from Saul, the house and wives of his predecessor, the kingdom of Israel and Judah. The inventory of gifts makes the sin not just a legal violation but an act of ingratitude against specific, enumerated divine generosity.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'I gave you your master's house and your master's wives into your arms... and if that were too little, I would add to you as much more (<em>wəʾōsipāh lākā kāhēnnâ wəḵāhēnnâ</em>).' The divine willingness to have given more is the counterfactual that indicts: the sin was not committed from deprivation. <em>wəʾōsipāh</em> — the Hiphil of <em>yāsap</em> (to add/increase) — indicates that YHWH's giving was not exhausted; David could have asked and received. The sin was committed against one who had given everything and would have given more.</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>bāzîṯā dəḇar-YHWH</strong>: 'You have despised the word (<em>dāḇār</em>) of YHWH.' The verb <em>bāzâ</em> means to treat as contemptible, to regard with disdain. The sin is characterized not first as a crime against Uriah but as contempt for YHWH's command. Three charges follow: <em>hikkîṯā ḇəḥereḇ</em> (you struck him with the sword), <em>wattiqaḥ ʾet-ʾišˀtô lǝḵā lěʾišˀâ</em> (you took his wife for yourself), <em>wahărağtô ḇəḥereḇ ḇənê ʿammôn</em> (you killed him by the Ammonites' sword). The three charges are presented in narrative order — the taking of Bathsheba (ch11:4) and the arranging of Uriah's death (11:14-15) — but the judgment places the murder last, as the escalating climax.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Now therefore the sword shall never depart from your house (<em>lō-ṯāsûr ḥereḇ mibêṯəḵā</em>), because you have despised me (<em>bəzîṯānî</em>) and have taken the wife of Uriah the Hittite.' The judicial sentence is proportional: David used the sword (through the Ammonites) to remove Uriah; the sword will not leave his house. <em>bəzîṯānî</em> (you have despised me) intensifies the accusation of v9: despising YHWH's word is identified as despising YHWH himself. The decree is prospective, spanning the rest of the narrative in 2 Samuel and into Kings.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Behold, I will raise up evil against you from your own house (<em>mēḇêṯəḵā</em>).' The instrument of judgment will come from within David's own family — the most painful possible form of retribution. <em>rāʿāh</em> here means both moral evil and calamity/disaster — the word encompasses both the wickedness that will arise from David's house and the suffering it will cause him. The fulfillment is Amnon's violation of Tamar (ch13), Absalom's murder of Amnon (13:28-29), and Absalom's rebellion (chs15-18).</p>",
    "12": "<p>'For you did it secretly (<em>bassāṯer</em>), but I will do this thing before all Israel and before the sun (<em>negeḏ kol-yiśrāʾēl wənegeḏ haššāmeš</em>).' The public/private contrast is the precise inverse of David's concealment strategy. The private sin — the letter of Uriah's death handed to him (11:14), the quiet appropriation of Bathsheba — is answered by public exposure. Absalom's fulfillment of v12 is narrated explicitly in 16:22 with the phrase <em>leeney kol-yisrael</em> (before all Israel).</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>ḥāṭāʾtî laYHWH</strong>: 'I have sinned against YHWH.' David's confession is three Hebrew words — the shortest and most direct confession in the OT. Nathan responds: <em>gam-YHWH heʿĕḇîr ḥaṭṭāʾṯəḵā lō ṯāmûṯ</em> (YHWH has also caused your sin to pass over — you will not die). The verb <em>heʿĕḇîr</em> — Hiphil of <em>ʿāḇar</em> (to pass over/cause to cross) — is a forensic term for the removal of judicial guilt. Ps 51, which the superscription assigns to this moment, expands the same act with vocabulary like <em>māḥāh</em> (blot out) and <em>kāḇas</em> (wash). The forgiveness is real and immediate; its consequences are not thereby cancelled (v14).</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Nevertheless, because by this deed you have utterly scorned YHWH (<em>nāʾōṣ niʾaṣtā</em>), the child who is born to you shall die.' The construction <em>nāʾōṣ niʾaṣtā</em> — infinitive absolute + finite verb — is an intensification formula meaning complete, thorough contempt. The verb <em>nāʾaṣ</em> is stronger than the <em>bāzâ</em> of v9; it means to blaspheme, to treat with the utmost contempt. The child's death is the consequence that vindicates YHWH's honor before the enemies who would use David's sin as occasion to blaspheme (<em>yənaʾăṣû</em>). The moral calculus is not that the child is punished in David's place but that the death addresses the public dishonor done to YHWH's name.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'YHWH struck the child that Uriah's wife bore to David, and it became sick.' The identification as 'Uriah's wife' rather than Bathsheba — even after she is now David's wife — echoes Nathan's accusation and keeps the moral frame visible throughout the narrative. The child's illness connects the judicial decree (v14) to observable providence.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'David therefore sought God (<em>waybaqqeš dāwid ʾeṯ-hāʾelōhîm</em>) on behalf of the child.' The verb <em>bāqaš</em> (to seek urgently/earnestly) combined with fasting (<em>wayyāṣom</em>) and prostration (<em>wəšākaḇ ʾārṣâ</em>, lying on the ground) depicts intercessory prayer at its most intense. The change of divine name — YHWH in v13-15, ʾelōhîm here — may reflect David's posture of supplication before the sovereign God rather than the covenantal name.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'The elders of his house stood beside him to raise him from the ground, but he would not, nor did he eat food with them.' The contrast between the elders' attempts and David's refusal dramatizes the depth of his intercession. The communal pressure to resume normal life — eating, rising — is resisted as long as the child lives. David's persistence in prayer is the model of the intercessor who will not stop until the outcome is known.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'On the seventh day the child died. And the servants of David were afraid to tell him that the child was dead.' The seventh-day death has covenantal resonance — the number of completion. The servants' fear (<em>yārēʾû</em>) to tell David reveals their uncertainty about his response: if he was so grieved while the child lived, what might he do when the child dies? Their reasoning (v18b) anticipates something extreme.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'But David saw that his servants were whispering together. And David understood that the child was dead.' David's perceptive discernment — reading the behavior of those around him to infer the fact before it is spoken — is a characteristic Davidic quality throughout 2 Samuel. <em>wayyāḇen dāwid</em> (David understood/discerned) uses the verb <em>bîn</em> (to discern, to understand by observing), the same root used in Prov 1:2-6 for wisdom.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Then David arose from the earth and washed and anointed himself and changed his clothes. And he went into the house of YHWH and worshiped. He then went to his own house. And when he asked, they set food before him, and he ate.' The sequence — arose, washed, anointed, changed, worshiped — is the reversal of mourning ritual (which involved fasting, uncleanliness, torn garments). The order of David's actions is theologically significant: he goes to the house of YHWH before his own house; worship precedes comfort. The servants' astonishment (v21) shows this reversal was counterintuitive.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'His servants said to him: What is this thing that you have done? You fasted and wept for the child while he was alive; but when the child died, you arose and ate food.' The servants' question opens the space for David's theology of prayer and providence. Their categories — fasting-while-alive, eating-after-death — are the conventional ones; David's explanation reverses the logic.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'I fasted and wept, for I said, Who knows whether YHWH will be gracious to me (<em>mî yōdēaʿ yaḥannēnî YHWH</em>), that the child may live?' The phrase <em>mî yōdēaʿ</em> (who knows?) expresses epistemic humility before YHWH's freedom to be gracious. The same formula occurs in Joel 2:14 and Jonah 3:9 — a pattern where <em>mî yōdēaʿ</em> functions as the basis for penitential prayer: YHWH is free to relent; therefore we ask. The verb <em>yāḥan</em> (to be gracious) is from the same root as <em>ḥen</em> (grace/favor) — David appealed to YHWH's character of favor.</p>",
    "23": "<p><strong>ʾănî hōlēk ʾēlāyw</strong>: 'I shall go to him, but he will not return to me.' This is one of the earliest expressions of personal eschatological hope in the OT. The certainty that the child will not return (<em>lō-yāšûḇ</em>) is paired with a prospective confidence: I am going to him (<em>hōlēk ʾēlāyw</em>). The verb <em>hālak</em> (to go) means here to die and arrive where the dead go — David's implicit belief in a post-death realm where personal continuity and reunion are possible. The statement is not merely resignation; it is oriented anticipation.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'David comforted his wife Bathsheba, and went in to her and lay with her, and she bore a son, and he called his name Solomon (<em>šəlōmōh</em>).' The name <em>šəlōmōh</em> is connected to <em>šālôm</em> (peace/wholeness) — the child of restoration carries the peace-name. The same root connects to Solomon's building of the Temple (1 Chr 22:9: a man of peace) and to the concept of completeness/fulfillment that his reign will represent. The restored relationship between David and Bathsheba produces the covenant-continuation heir.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'YHWH loved him (<em>wayyeʾăhāḇēhû YHWH</em>) and sent a message by Nathan the prophet. So he called his name Jedidiah (<em>yəḏîḏyāh</em>), because of YHWH.' The name <em>yəḏîḏyāh</em> (beloved of YHWH) is YHWH's own naming of the child, transmitted through the same prophet who pronounced judgment. Nathan's second appearance in ch12 is an act of grace — the prophet of judgment becomes the prophet of divine love for the new child. The divine name <em>yāḏîḏ</em> (beloved) belongs to the root of intimate affection; it appears in Ps 60:5 and Ps 127:2 (he grants sleep to his beloved).</p>",
    "26": "<p>'Now Joab fought against Rabbah of the Ammonites and captured the royal city.' Rabbah was the Ammonite capital (modern Amman, Jordan). The battle that David had abandoned to commit adultery and arrange Uriah's murder is now completed by Joab, who summons David to claim the victory. The narrative structure places the moral crisis of chs 11-12 within the frame of the Ammonite war — the war that David missed (11:1) and that is now resolved after the judgment (12:26-31).</p>",
    "27": "<p>'And Joab sent messengers to David and said, I have fought against Rabbah; moreover, I have taken the city of waters.' Joab's message is strategically diplomatic: he has taken the water supply (the fortified water source that the main city depended on), ensuring David's victory if he comes now. Joab explicitly credits the final conquest to David — <em>pen-ʾeqqaḥ ʾănî ʾeṯ-hāʿîr wəniqrāʾ šəmî ʿāleyhā</em> (lest I take the city and my name be called on it, v28). The general defers the honor to the king.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'Now therefore gather the rest of the people together and encamp against the city and take it, lest I take the city and it be called by my name.' Joab's concern that the city not be named after him reflects ANE custom of attributing military victories to the king (the naming convention). His deference protects David's honor and the political narrative — even after the moral failure of ch11, David's kingship requires a public victory to consolidate.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'So David gathered all the people and went to Rabbah and fought against it and took it.' The restoration of David to his military role marks the return to narrative normalcy. The intervening chapters (11:2–12:25) have been a parenthesis within the Ammonite war frame — the war resumes and concludes as if it had continued normally, even though everything between its opening and close has been transformed by the crisis.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'And he took the crown of their king from his head. The weight of it was a talent of gold, and in it was a precious stone, and it was placed on David's head.' The Ammonite king's crown transferred to David's head is the material embodiment of the military and political victory. A talent of gold (approximately 75 lbs) would be an actual weight; commentators note this may be a ceremonial crown placed briefly on David's head rather than worn habitually. The Hebrew <em>malkām</em> may be the name of the Ammonite god Milcom rather than 'their king' — if so, the crown of the Ammonite deity is placed on the Israelite king, a statement of YHWH's supremacy over the foreign god.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'And he brought out the people who were in it and set them to labor with saws and iron picks and iron axes and made them toil at the brick kilns. And thus he did to all the cities of the Ammonites.' The treatment of the Ammonites — <em>wayyāśem bammēgērâ... ûbəḥārūṣê habbarzel</em> (he set them to saws and iron threshing sledges) — is the forced labor characteristic of conquest. The textual tradition is debated: some manuscripts read 'he sawed them with saws' (a harsher interpretation); the MKT follows the sense of forced labor rather than dismemberment, consistent with David's generally measured treatment of defeated peoples.</p>"
  },
  "13": {
    "1": "<p>'After this, Absalom son of David had a beautiful sister (<em>ʾāḥôṯ yapâ</em>) named Tamar, and Amnon son of David fell in love with her (<em>wayeʾĕhāḇehā ʾamnôn</em>).' The chapter opens with family relationships: Absalom and Tamar share the same mother; Amnon is Tamar's half-brother, David's firstborn by a different wife. The use of <em>ʾāhēḇ</em> (love) for Amnon's feeling is immediately qualified by the narrative — what follows will show this was not covenant love but consuming desire. The beauty of Tamar and the wrongness of Amnon's desire are juxtaposed in v1's opening.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Amnon was so tormented (<em>wayyiṣṣer ləʾamnôn</em>) by his desire for Tamar that he became ill (<em>wayyiḥleh</em>), for she was a virgin (<em>bəṯûlâ</em>) and it seemed impossible (<em>wayyibbāṣēr ḇəʿênê ʾamnôn</em>) for him to do anything to her.' The verb <em>ṣārar</em> (to be constrained/distressed) describes Amnon's psychological state. The key term <em>bəṯûlâ</em> (virgin) establishes Tamar's legal status — a virgin daughter under her father's protection, accessible through no normal channel. <em>wayyibbāṣēr</em> (it was withheld/impossible) from <em>bāṣar</em> (to cut off, restrain): the legitimate path to Tamar was cut off.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'But Amnon had a friend named Jonadab, son of Shimeah, David's brother; and Jonadab was a very shrewd man (<em>ḥākām məʾōd</em>).' The description of Jonadab as <em>ḥākām</em> (wise/shrewd) is ironic: he is clever in the service of wickedness — the opposite of the wisdom of Proverbs. His <em>ḥokmâ</em> is <em>ḥokmâ rāʿāh</em> (evil wisdom), the cunning that finds ways to accomplish what ought not to be done.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'He said to Amnon: Why are you, the king's son, growing thinner (<em>dallôṯ</em>) day after day? Won't you tell me?' The term <em>dallôṯ</em> (thin/declining, from <em>dālal</em> to be low/reduced) describes physical deterioration from emotional distress. Jonadab's question is sympathetic but his purpose is to enable sin. His identity as David's nephew (Shimeah is David's brother) means this scheme involves the extended royal family in the conspiracy.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Jonadab said to him: Lie down on your bed and pretend to be ill. When your father comes to visit you, say to him, Let my sister Tamar come and give me food to eat, and prepare the food in my sight, that I may see it and eat it from her hand.' Jonadab's scheme uses the conventions of illness-hospitality and family care to create access to Tamar. The request <em>mittādehā</em> (from her hand) specifies personal delivery — the detail that will isolate Tamar in Amnon's presence.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'So Amnon lay down and pretended to be ill. And when the king came to see him, Amnon said to the king, Please let my sister Tamar come and make a couple of cakes (<em>šətê lḇiḇōṯ</em>) in my sight, that I may eat from her hand.' The <em>lǝḇiḇāh</em> (cake/heart-shaped bread) appears only here in the OT; its connection to the root <em>lēḇ</em> (heart) may carry the irony that Amnon requests heart-cakes from the woman he claims to love. David's compliance with the request — without apparent suspicion — marks his failure of oversight.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Then David sent to Tamar's house, saying, Go to your brother Amnon's house and prepare food for him.' David's instruction is the unwitting mechanism of harm. His sending of Tamar to Amnon's house sets the chain in motion. The phrase <em>bêṯ ʾamnôn ʾāḥîḵā</em> (the house of your brother Amnon) — using the familial term — is the cover under which the assault is planned.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'So Tamar went to her brother Amnon's house, where he was lying down. And she took dough and kneaded it and made cakes in his sight and baked the cakes.' Tamar's compliance with the request is complete and innocent — she fulfills the role of caring sister without any knowledge of the scheme. The domestic detail (kneading, baking) grounds the scene in normal household activity, making the sudden assault (v14) more jarring.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'And she took the pan and emptied it out before him, but he refused to eat. And Amnon said, Send out everyone from me. So everyone went out from him.' The refusal to eat is the signal that the scheme was never about food. The clearing of the house (<em>hōṣîʾû kol-ʾîš mēʿālay</em>, send out everyone from me) isolates Tamar. The servants depart without apparent concern — the king's son's request was not unusual to them.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Then Amnon said to Tamar, Bring the food into the chamber, that I may eat from your hand. And Tamar took the cakes she had made and brought them into the chamber to Amnon her brother.' The movement from the main room to the inner chamber (<em>haḥāḏer</em>) is the last movement before the assault. Tamar follows, still without apparent alarm — the setting remained within the realm of family care.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'But when she brought them near him to eat, he took hold of her (<em>wayeḥĕzeq-bāh</em>) and said to her, Come, lie with me, my sister.' The verb <em>ḥāzaq</em> (to grasp firmly, to overpower) indicates forceful physical restraint — the first moment of explicit coercion. His words use the familial term <em>ʾăḥôṯî</em> (my sister) alongside the demand, which makes the request a double violation: sexual assault of a sibling. Tamar's response in vv12-13 is a composed, reasoned refusal.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'She answered him, No, my brother, do not violate me (<em>ʾal-tənannēnî</em>), for such a thing is not done in Israel (<em>lō-yēʿāśeh ḵēn bəyiśrāʾēl</em>); do not do this outrageous thing (<em>nəḇālâ</em>).' <strong>nəḇālâ</strong> is the key term: it means an outrage against the social-covenant order, a gross violation of what Israel's communal life requires. The term appears in Gen 34:7 (Dinah's violation), Deut 22:21 (sexual immorality), and Judg 19-20 (the Levite's concubine). Tamar names the act with the correct theological and social vocabulary. <em>lō-yēʿāśeh ḵēn bəyiśrāʾēl</em> — not done this way in Israel — invokes the covenant community's standards as the frame for her refusal.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'And I, where would I carry my shame (<em>ʾănî ʾānāh ʾôlîḵ ʾeṯ-ḥerpāṯî</em>)? And as for you, you would be as one of the outrageous fools (<em>kəʾaḥaḏ hannəḇālîm</em>) in Israel. Now therefore, please speak to the king, for he will not withhold me from you.' Tamar's second argument: the social consequences for both. <em>ḥerpâ</em> (shame, disgrace, reproach) — the word used for the permanent social stigma of sexual violation. Her counterproposal — ask the king — indicates she believed a legitimate marriage might be possible (though Lev 18:9 and Deut 27:22 prohibit half-sibling marriage; her suggestion may be desperation or a legal tradition allowing exceptions).</p>",
    "14": "<p>'But he would not listen to her, and being stronger than she, he violated her (<em>wayəḥazzēq mimmennāh wayyiškaḇ ʾōṯāh wayyannahā</em>) and lay with her.' The verb sequence is unambiguous: <em>ḥāzaq</em> (overpowered), <em>šāḵaḇ</em> (lay with), <em>ʿinnāh</em> (violated/humiliated). The verb <em>ʿānāh</em> (Piel: to violate, to humble by force) is the technical term for sexual violence in the OT (Gen 34:2; Deut 22:24,29; Ezek 22:10-11). The narrative names what happened with legal precision.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Then Amnon hated her with very great hatred (<em>wayyiśnāʾehā ʾamnôn śinʾāh gəḏôlāh məʾōd</em>), so that the hatred with which he hated her was greater than the love with which he had loved her.' The sentence is one of the most precise psychological observations in the OT. <em>śinʾâ</em> (hatred) is placed against <em>ʾahăḇâ</em> (love) — the verbal contrast exposes what Amnon's 'love' actually was: not covenant commitment but consuming desire that, when fulfilled, turned to loathing. The fulfilled desire without covenant is characterized not by satisfaction but by revulsion — a pattern that distinguishes <em>ʾahăḇâ</em> (covenant love) from <em>ḥāšaq</em> or mere desire.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'And Amnon said to her, Get up! Go (<em>qûmî lēḵî</em>)!' But she said to him, No, my brother, for this wrong in sending me away (<em>hārāʿāh haggəḏôlāh hazzōʾt lǝšalləḥēnî</em>) is greater than the other that you did to me.' Tamar identifies the second act — the dismissal — as a greater wrong than the first. In ANE and Israelite law, a man who violated an unengaged virgin was required to marry her (Deut 22:28-29) — the dismissal would leave her without legal recourse and in permanent social disgrace. She is naming the legal outcome her rejection creates.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'But he would not listen to her. He called the young man who served him and said, Put this woman out of my presence and bolt the door after her.' <em>haššillîḥāh</em> (send her out) — the same root used for divorce in Deut 24; the association is part of the shame: Amnon treats her as a discarded wife without the legal status. <em>nəʿal haḏdeleṯ ʾaḥărêhā</em> (bolt the door after her) — the locking of the door finalizes the exclusion.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Now she was wearing a long robe (<em>kəṯōneṯ passîm</em>) with long sleeves, for thus were the virgin daughters of the king dressed.' The <em>kəṯōneṯ passîm</em> is the same garment worn by Joseph (Gen 37:3) — a distinctive garment marking status. For David's virgin daughters it signified royal virginity and protection. Its tearing in the next verse is both a literal act and a symbolic enactment of what has been taken.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'And Tamar put ashes (<em>ʾēper</em>) on her head and tore the long robe (<em>wattiqraʿ kəṯōneṯ happasîm</em>) that she wore. And she laid her hand on her head and went away, crying aloud as she went.' The mourning ritual Tamar performs — ash on head, torn garment, hand on head, wailing — is the full vocabulary of grief. The torn <em>kəṯōneṯ passîm</em> is particularly significant: the garment of protected virginity is torn, enacting publicly what has happened privately. Her public mourning is an act of witness.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>šōmēmâ</strong>: 'And Tamar lived, a desolate woman (<em>šōmēmâ</em>), in her brother Absalom's house.' The word <em>šōmēmâ</em> (desolate/devastated) is the same term used for the desolation of a land under divine judgment (Isa 49:8; Jer 12:11; Lam 1:13). Applied to a person, it means the devastation of personhood — the reduction of a full human life to a condition of ruin. Tamar sits desolate in Absalom's house: alive but in a state the text names with the language of national catastrophe. The word choice is the text's theological evaluation of what was done to her.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'When King David heard of all these things, he was very angry (<em>wayyiḥar lô məʾōd</em>), but he would not punish his son Amnon, because he loved him (<em>kî-ʾăhēḇô kî bəḵōrô hûʾ</em>), for he was his firstborn.' David's failure here is judicial: as king, he administered justice to all Israel (8:15); as father, he failed to administer it within his own household. The stated reason — love of his firstborn — is the same motivation that produced the failure of Eli (1 Sam 3:13) and of the corrupt judges generally: personal affection overriding judicial obligation. The text offers no mitigation.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'But Absalom spoke to Amnon neither good nor bad, for Absalom hated Amnon (<em>kî-śānēʾ ʾabšālôm ʾeṯ-ʾamnôn</em>) because he had violated his sister Tamar.' Absalom's silence — speaking neither good nor bad — is the silence of a man who has resolved on a course of action and is waiting for the right moment. <em>ʿal-dǝḇar ʿannôṯ ʾeṯ-tāmār ʾăḥōṯô</em> (because of the violation of his sister Tamar) — the stated motivation is the protection of his sister and revenge for the wrong that David failed to address.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'After two full years (<em>šənāyim šānîm</em>) Absalom had sheepshearers at Baal-hazor, which is near Ephraim.' Two years of silence precede the act — the time in which Absalom nursed his hatred (v22) and planned. Baal-hazor is identified with Tell ʿAsur, approximately 15 miles north of Jerusalem, near Ephraim. The sheepshearing festival was a time of feasting and relative security — the occasion Absalom chose for the murder.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'And Absalom came to the king and said, Behold, your servant has sheepshearers. Please let the king and his servants go with your servant.' Absalom's invitation to David is deliberate misdirection — he wants the king's presence to lend legitimacy to the gathering and to gain access to Amnon. David's initial refusal (v25) is the opening for the specific request that follows.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'But the king said to Absalom, No, my son, let us not all go, lest we be burdensome to you. He pressed him, but he would not go and gave him his blessing.' David's reluctance — expressed as concern about the burden of the full court attending — and Absalom's persistent request (<em>wayyiprāṣ-bô</em>, he pressed him) show Absalom's insistence on getting Amnon specifically to the gathering.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'Then Absalom said, If not, please let my brother Amnon go with us.' And the king said to him, Why should he go with you?' Absalom's specific request for Amnon draws David's attention to the unusual nature of the invitation. David's question — why should Amnon specifically go? — suggests some awareness that a targeted request deserves scrutiny, though he ultimately concedes.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'But Absalom pressed him until he let Amnon and all the king's sons go with him.' <em>wayyiprāṣēhû</em> — the same verb as v25 (he pressed/urged insistently). Absalom's persistence overcomes David's hesitation. The presence of all the king's sons protects Absalom from suspicion — it looks like a family gathering, not a targeted assassination.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'Then Absalom commanded his servants, Mark when Amnon's heart is merry with wine (<em>kəṭôḇ lēḇ-ʾamnôn bayyāyin</em>), and when I say to you, Strike Amnon, then kill him. Do not fear; have I not commanded you? Be courageous and be valiant.' <em>kəṭôḇ lēḇ bayyāyin</em> (when the heart is good with wine) — the phrase used for festive inebriation; the same condition Nabal was in when Abigail intervened (1 Sam 25:36). Absalom waits for the moment of vulnerability. The instruction to his servants — fear not, I command you — frames the murder as an authorized act of justice.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'And the servants of Absalom did to Amnon as Absalom had commanded. Then all the king's sons arose, and each mounted his mule and fled.' The assassination is narrated tersely. The flight of all the king's sons on their mules creates the false report that all the king's sons are dead (v30) — the rapid departure of the group is misread as indicating general slaughter.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'While they were on the way, news came to David, All the king's sons have been killed, and not one of them is left.' The garbled report — all the sons dead — is the misreading of a mass flight. The principle that early reports in crisis are often exaggerated is embedded in the narrative; Jonadab's correction (v32-33) arrives to provide the more accurate account.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'Then the king arose and tore his garments and lay on the ground. And all his servants who were standing by tore their garments.' David's mourning ritual — torn garments, prostration — is the appropriate response to the death-news. The communal mourning of the servants mirrors the king's.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'But Jonadab the son of Shimeah, David's brother, answered, Let not my lord suppose that they have killed all the young men, the king's sons, for Amnon alone is dead. For by the command of Absalom this has been determined from the day he violated his sister Tamar.' Jonadab's clarification is accurate but also incriminating of himself: he knew the plan had been set from 'the day Tamar was violated' — suggesting he had information about Absalom's intent and said nothing. His earlier role in enabling the scheme (v3-5) and his now-demonstrated knowledge of the aftermath put him in an uncomfortable position.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'Now therefore let not my lord the king take it to heart to suppose that all the king's sons are dead, for Amnon alone is dead.' Jonadab's twice-stated correction — only Amnon is dead — is reassurance designed also to manage David's response. His knowledge of the plan's specific target confirms advance information.</p>",
    "34": "<p>'But Absalom fled. And the young man who kept the watch lifted up his eyes and looked, and behold, many people were coming from the road behind him by the side of the mountain.' The watchman's report of people coming down from the hill road allows the king to receive the returning sons before he has fully processed the news.</p>",
    "35": "<p>'And Jonadab said to the king, Behold, the king's sons have come; as your servant said, so it has come about.' Jonadab's vindication of his own report is self-serving: he is positioning himself as a trustworthy counselor even though he had enabled the original crime. His role in the narrative is consistently that of shrewd self-preservation at others' expense.</p>",
    "36": "<p>'And as soon as he had finished speaking, the king's sons came and lifted up their voices and wept. And the king also and all his servants wept very bitterly.' The family grief is genuine: though only Amnon is dead, the event has fractured the household irrevocably. Absalom is now a fugitive; the sword that Nathan decreed (v10) has entered the house.</p>",
    "37": "<p>'But Absalom fled and went to Talmai the son of Ammihud, king of Geshur (<em>wayyāmāṯ ʾeṯ-māʿăḵāh</em>). And David mourned for his son day after day.' Geshur was a small Aramean kingdom northeast of the Sea of Galilee. Absalom's mother Maacah was the daughter of Talmai king of Geshur (3:3) — Absalom fled to his maternal grandfather. The refuge is both geographically safe and genealogically connected, placing him beyond David's immediate reach.</p>",
    "38": "<p>'So Absalom fled and went to Geshur, and was there three years.' Three years in exile — the same temporal unit that the Gibeonite famine will span (21:1). The three-year period allows Absalom to develop his estrangement from David into a political strategy. David's inability to act decisively (to punish Amnon, then to recall Absalom) reflects the same paralysis that characterized his response to Tamar's violation.</p>",
    "39": "<p>'And the spirit of the king longed to go out to Absalom (<em>watəḵal nēpeš-haMMeleḵ lāṣēṯ ʾel-ʾabšālôm</em>), because he was comforted about Amnon, since he was dead.' The verb <em>kālâ</em> (to be spent/consumed/finished) with <em>nēpeš</em> (soul/desire) describes David's consuming longing — his desire to go to Absalom had worn him out. The grief for Amnon has reached its end (<em>nāḥam</em>, he was comforted, meaning the acute grief had passed); what remains is the longing for the living son who fled. The tension between justice (Absalom killed his brother) and paternal love drives the next chapter.</p>"
  }
}

